<font color="#FF0000">JUST MY OPINION</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jan 23 11:27:26 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
<br>
you all have seen me here once or twice before.  I feel the need to speak up as one for which the Tomb has a presonal feeling.  As the daughter of an MIA- the tomb is a sacred place to me. A place of &quot;he just may be the one there&quot;.  A place I can find peace and solice when I have nothing else to turn to.  For many of us, it is a place where our dreams of having our loved ones home may be a little more realistic than the not knowing at all.  I too have mixed emotions of exhuming the remains, however, if there is even a 1% chance that this fine man could be identified and returned to his family, tradition must set aside for what is the right thing to do.  I hope I have not offended anyone here, for that is not my intent at all; I just thought you'd like the prospective of someone who lives with the word Missing In Action tatooed on her heart until the day that he finally comes home.
<p><code>--   (Kimberly) </code><p>


